	keepReadingHtml={`Start with the <a href="https://fathersheartbible.com/read" style="color: var(--color-brand);" class="hover:underline">whole Bible free online with audio</a>, learn <a href="/the-fathers-heart-bible/" style="color: var(--color-brand);" class="hover:underline">why the Father's Heart Bible™ exists</a>, or get oriented with our <a href="/guides/" style="color: var(--color-brand);" class="hover:underline">Bible reading guides</a> — including <a href="/guides/how-to-pray/" style="color: var(--color-brand);" class="hover:underline">how to pray</a> and <a href="/verses/" style="color: var(--color-brand);" class="hover:underline">verses by topic</a>. Or meet the Father in another season through the rest of the <a href="/bible-for/" style="color: var(--color-brand);" class="hover:underline">A Father For series</a>.`}
	faqs={[
		{ question: `What are good Bible verses for the incarcerated?`, answer: `Psalm 146:7 (the Father sets prisoners free), Isaiah 61:1 and Luke 4:18 (freedom for the captives), Hebrews 13:3 (remember those in prison), 2 Corinthians 5:17 (a new creation), John 8:36 (if the Son sets you free, you are free indeed), Romans 8:38-39 (nothing can separate you from God's love), and Psalm 139:7-10 (there is no place He is not with you) all speak straight to what the incarcerated carry. Read and hear them free in the Father's Heart Bible™ at fathersheartbible.com/read.` },
		{ question: `What does the Bible say about people in prison?`, answer: `Scripture says God remembers and frees prisoners. Psalm 146:7 says the Father sets the prisoners free, Hebrews 13:3 commands God's people to remember those in prison as if they were there with them, and in Luke 4:18 Jesus names freeing prisoners as central to His mission. The Father's Heart Bible™ reveals God as a Father who reaches through any wall — read those passages free, with audio, at fathersheartbible.com/read.` },
		{ question: `Does God still love me even with my record?`, answer: `Yes — and that's the whole point. You are not your worst day or your sentence. Romans 8:38-39 says nothing can separate you from God's love, and 2 Corinthians 5:17 says that in Christ you become a new creation — the old gone, the new come. In the Father's Heart Bible™ you meet God as a Father who has not forgotten you and calls you His own right now. Read it free at fathersheartbible.com/read.` },
		{ question: `What does the Bible say about a fresh start after prison?`, answer: `The Bible is full of new beginnings. 2 Corinthians 5:17 promises that in Christ the old is gone and the new has come, and John 8:36 says that whoever the Son sets free is free indeed — a freedom that can begin in the heart before reentry ever does. The Father's Heart Bible™ shows a Father who restores, not a warden who keeps score. Read and listen free at fathersheartbible.com/read.` },
		{ question: `Are there Bible verses for the families of the incarcerated?`, answer: `Yes. Psalm 139:7-10 promises there is no distance where God is not already holding you, Romans 8:38-39 says nothing can separate you or your loved one from His love, and Hebrews 13:3 calls God's people to remember those in prison and their families. Families can read along together, free with audio, at fathersheartbible.com/read — a way to stay connected across the miles.` },
		{ question: `Is there a free Bible with audio I can use in prison or when I come home?`, answer: `Yes. The Father's Heart Bible™ is free to read and listen to online — no account, no purchase, no cost. Many can reach it on facility tablets or once they're home at fathersheartbible.com/read, and families on the outside can read or hear any book to stay connected during a sentence and through reentry.` },
		{ question: `What makes the Father's Heart Bible™ different for the incarcerated?`, answer: `It's the first English translation to reveal God as Father wherever Scripture reveals Him as Father — so instead of meeting a warden keeping score of your failures, you meet a Father whose love reaches through any wall. For someone carrying a label and a sentence, that reframes everything: you come to the Bible as a loved child who has not been forgotten, not a case number. Read it free at fathersheartbible.com/read.` },
	]}
